<td class="mbox-image">
<div style="width: 52px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="image" title="Question book-new.svg"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" width="50" height="39" border="0" /></a></div>
</td>
<td class="mbox-text" style="">This article <b>relies largely or entirely upon a <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:CITE" title="Wikipedia:CITE" class="mw-redirect">single source</a></b>. Please help <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Rational_trigonometry&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Rational_trigonometry&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow">improve this article</a> by introducing appropriate <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:CITE" title="Wikipedia:CITE" class="mw-redirect">citations</a> of additional sources. <small><i>(January 2009)</i></small></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><i><b>Divine Proportions: Rational Trigonometry to Universal Geometry</b></i> is a book by Norman J. Wildberger, an outspoken critic of traditional mathematics, presenting his reformulation of <a href="/wiki/Trigonometry" title="Trigonometry">trigonometry</a>. Wildberger holds a Ph.D. in mathematics from <a href="/wiki/Yale_University" title="Yale University">Yale University</a>, and taught at <a href="/wiki/Stanford_University" title="Stanford University">Stanford University</a> from 1984 to 1986 and at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Toronto" title="University of Toronto">University of Toronto</a> from 1986 to 1989; he is currently an associate professor of mathematics at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_New_South_Wales" title="University of New South Wales">University of New South Wales</a>, <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a>.</p>
